and how it developed.


2289
01:56:13.472 --> 01:56:15.472
Insdorf:
There are people struggling


2290
01:56:15.472 --> 01:56:19.097
in one way or another
for freedom in these movies.


2291
01:56:19.097 --> 01:56:23.847
Give... us free.

2292
01:56:23.847 --> 01:56:25.972
He doesn't take freedom
for granted.


2293
01:56:27.388 --> 01:56:29.680
Kaminski:
Liberty and equality,


2294
01:56:29.680 --> 01:56:32.056
the Constitution,

2295
01:56:32.056 --> 01:56:33.639
and the rights
of the individual.


2296
01:56:33.639 --> 01:56:35.181
( cheering )

2297
01:56:35.181 --> 01:56:38.014
Kaminski:
He's evolved
as a filmmaker.


2298
01:56:38.014 --> 01:56:41.513
"Amistad" and "Lincoln"
and "Bridge of Spies"


2299
01:56:41.513 --> 01:56:43.139
are all about
the rule of law.


2300
01:56:43.139 --> 01:56:46.014
They're all about
the rights of even people


2301
01:56:46.014 --> 01:56:49.263
who are either brought here
against their will


2302
01:56:49.263 --> 01:56:54.014
or come here to be a soldier
in an opposing army


2303
01:56:54.014 --> 01:56:55.680
and are caught.

2304
01:56:55.680 --> 01:56:58.430
The law fully covers
everyone.


2305
01:56:58.430 --> 01:56:59.722
Tom:
We were supposed to show


2306
01:56:59.722 --> 01:57:02.056
he had a capable defense,
which we did.


2307
01:57:02.056 --> 01:57:04.722
Why are you citing
the goddamn Constitution
at me?


2308
01:57:04.722 --> 01:57:06.305
Tom, if you look me
in the eye


2309
01:57:06.305 --> 01:57:08.181
and tell me
we don't have grounds


2310
01:57:08.181 --> 01:57:09.555
for an appeal,
I'll drop it right now.


2311
01:57:09.555 --> 01:57:11.805
I'm not saying that.
You know what I'm saying.


2312
01:57:11.805 --> 01:57:13.805
Tom is saying
there's a cost
to these things.


2313
01:57:13.805 --> 01:57:15.680
That's right.

2314
01:57:15.680 --> 01:57:18.680
A cost to both
your family and your firm.


2315
01:57:18.680 --> 01:57:20.347
Spielberg:
I really believe
in this country,


2316
01:57:20.347 --> 01:57:21.847
and I always have.

2317
01:57:21.847 --> 01:57:24.056
And it just resonated
throughout my work--


2318
01:57:24.056 --> 01:57:25.931
wanting to tell
American stories,


2319
01:57:25.931 --> 01:57:28.722
wanting to tell stories
about principled,
ethical people


2320
01:57:28.722 --> 01:57:30.555
who, against all advice

2321
01:57:30.555 --> 01:57:33.764
and against
most everyone else's
better judgment,


2322
01:57:33.764 --> 01:57:36.639
just proceed to do
the right thing.


2323
01:57:36.639 --> 01:57:40.764
I'm sure that sounds like
I'm this kind of, you know,


2324
01:57:40.764 --> 01:57:44.889
idealist or some sort
of a patriot,


2325
01:57:44.889 --> 01:57:46.889
but I am a patriot.

2326
01:57:46.889 --> 01:57:49.472
And I'm somewhat
of an idealist, too.


2327
01:57:49.472 --> 01:57:52.555
Say all we done
is show the world


2328
01:57:52.555 --> 01:57:54.889
that democracy
isn't chaos.


2329
01:57:57.597 --> 01:58:01.222
That there is a great
invisible strength


2330
01:58:01.222 --> 01:58:03.181
in a people's union.

2331
01:58:03.181 --> 01:58:05.764
Say we've shown
that a people can endure


2332
01:58:05.764 --> 01:58:09.513
awful sacrifice
and yet cohere.


2333
01:58:09.513 --> 01:58:12.181
Mightn't that save
at least the idea
of democracy,


2334
01:58:12.181 --> 01:58:14.555
to aspire to?

2335
01:58:14.555 --> 01:58:17.388
Eventually to become
worthy of?


2336
01:58:17.388 --> 01:58:19.430
Daniel Day-Lewis:
The first thing that
you have to overcome


2337
01:58:19.430 --> 01:58:21.555
is the reluctance
to even approach Lincoln


2338
01:58:21.555 --> 01:58:24.097
because he's such
a mighty figure.


2339
01:58:24.097 --> 01:58:26.931
His experience as a president
was in, you know,


2340
01:58:26.931 --> 01:58:30.097
one of the greatest crises
that this country's ever known.


2341
01:58:30.097 --> 01:58:33.014
And so, undoubtedly,
of course,


2342
01:58:33.014 --> 01:58:36.847
he made decisions that were
extremely unpalatable


2343
01:58:36.847 --> 01:58:38.597
to many, many people.

2344
01:58:38.597 --> 01:58:42.639
We are
absolutely guaranteed
to lose the whole thing.


2345
01:58:42.639 --> 01:58:45.847
We don't need a goddamned
abolition amendment.


2346
01:58:45.847 --> 01:58:48.181
Leave the Constitution
alone!


2347
01:58:48.181 --> 01:58:50.305
James:
...peace commissioners
appear today, or--


2348
01:58:50.305 --> 01:58:51.805
( overlapping voices )

2349
01:58:51.805 --> 01:58:53.139
( argument stops )

2350
01:58:54.388 --> 01:58:57.139
I can't listen
to this anymore.


2351
01:58:58.764 --> 01:59:02.056
I can't accomplish
a goddamn thing


2352
01:59:02.056 --> 01:59:04.513
of any human
meaning or worth


2353
01:59:04.513 --> 01:59:08.305
until we cure
ourselves of slavery


2354
01:59:08.305 --> 01:59:11.847
and end
this pestilential war!


2355
01:59:11.847 --> 01:59:15.263
And whether any of you
or anyone else knows it,


2356
01:59:15.263 --> 01:59:17.847
I know I need this!

2357
01:59:17.847 --> 01:59:21.347
This amendment
is that cure!


2358
01:59:21.347 --> 01:59:23.263
Steven worked a long time

2359
01:59:23.263 --> 01:59:25.722
to find where the story was
to tell it.


2360
01:59:25.722 --> 01:59:29.555
Kushner: And it took guts
for Steven to make a movie
about Abraham Lincoln


2361
01:59:29.555 --> 01:59:33.847
in which Lincoln
shares top billing with
the House of Representatives.


2362
01:59:33.847 --> 01:59:36.263
Doris Kearns Goodwin:
He had faith that if he told
a story


2363
01:59:36.263 --> 01:59:39.513
that is about democracy
and it's about messiness
and politics--


2364
01:59:39.513 --> 01:59:41.680
and people
are on different sides
of the issue,


2365
01:59:41.680 --> 01:59:43.680
and people
who were Democrats then
are Republicans now,


2366
01:59:43.680 --> 01:59:45.222
and Republicans now
were Democrats then,


2367
01:59:45.222 --> 01:59:47.847
was pretty confusing
for people to get a sense


2368
01:59:47.847 --> 01:59:49.513
right away
of what the story was.


2369
01:59:49.513 --> 01:59:52.222
But he somehow thought
if the American people


2370
01:59:52.222 --> 01:59:54.639
can feel this man
and feel what he was doing,


2371
01:59:54.639 --> 01:59:57.680
they'll see what democracy is
when it really works.


2372
01:59:57.680 --> 01:59:59.931
Schuyler:
A motion has been made
to bring the bill


2373
01:59:59.931 --> 02:00:02.263
for the 13th Amendment
to a vote.


2374
02:00:02.263 --> 02:00:04.263
- Do I hear a second?
- I second the motion.


2375
02:00:04.263 --> 02:00:06.555
- ( gravel bangs )
- So moved, so ordered.


2376
02:00:06.555 --> 02:00:09.931
And in the end,
it's not Lincoln's triumph


2377
02:00:09.931 --> 02:00:12.222
that's pushed to the fore
in the film.


2378
02:00:12.222 --> 02:00:14.097
I think what's really
pushed to the fore


2379
02:00:14.097 --> 02:00:16.555
is that it's a triumph
of democracy.


2380
02:00:16.555 --> 02:00:20.847
The part assigned to me
is to raise the flag.


2381
02:00:20.847 --> 02:00:25.764
And when up,
it'll be for the people
to keep it up.


2382
02:00:28.513 --> 02:00:29.805
That's my speech.

2383
02:00:29.805 --> 02:00:32.889
( crowd laughing,
applauding )


2384
