02:19:01.097 --> 02:19:02.513
It'd be impossible.

2750
02:19:05.014 --> 02:19:08.139
Kennedy:
Steven looks
at movies constantly


2751
02:19:08.139 --> 02:19:10.430
and over and over
and over again,


2752
02:19:10.430 --> 02:19:14.263
referencing shots
and framing and ideas.


2753
02:19:14.263 --> 02:19:16.972
That's something Steven does
all the time.


2754
02:19:16.972 --> 02:19:18.513
( boat horn blaring )

2755
02:19:20.805 --> 02:19:23.513
Spielberg:
Great filmmakers' works
live on to create


2756
02:19:23.513 --> 02:19:27.014
tremendous moments
of inspiration.


2757
02:19:27.014 --> 02:19:29.847
And so, one of the films
I still see every year


2758
02:19:29.847 --> 02:19:31.764
is "Lawrence of Arabia."

2759
02:19:31.764 --> 02:19:33.722
( music playing )

2760
02:19:39.722 --> 02:19:42.805
The shots,
the sheer vistas,


2761
02:19:42.805 --> 02:19:46.139
and the portrait
of such a complex character,


2762
02:19:46.139 --> 02:19:48.263
it's pure moviemaking.

2763
02:19:48.263 --> 02:19:49.847
Hey!

2764
02:19:49.847 --> 02:19:53.388
Hey! Hey! Hey!

2765
02:20:00.139 --> 02:20:02.056
Who are you?

2766
02:20:04.097 --> 02:20:07.097
Who are you?

2767
02:20:07.097 --> 02:20:08.805
Steven has always
wanted to work


2768
02:20:08.805 --> 02:20:12.430
in a kind of big, you know,
historical canvass like that,


2769
02:20:12.430 --> 02:20:15.222
and it took many movies
before he accomplished


2770
02:20:15.222 --> 02:20:19.222
that level
of masterly filmmaking.


2771
02:20:19.222 --> 02:20:21.931
Spielberg:
Many years ago, Pauline Kael
gave me a really great review


2772
02:20:21.931 --> 02:20:24.097
on "Sugarland Express,"
but she said,


2773
02:20:24.097 --> 02:20:26.680
"Whatever's on the surface
might be all that is there.


2774
02:20:26.680 --> 02:20:28.181
There may be nothing
behind that."


2775
02:20:28.181 --> 02:20:30.430
And she was
absolutely right.


2776
02:20:30.430 --> 02:20:33.805
I hadn't grown up yet
through the movies.


2777
02:20:33.805 --> 02:20:35.972
That was going to come
in time.


2778
02:20:35.972 --> 02:20:38.222
( music playing )

2779
02:20:42.472 --> 02:20:46.263
Maslin:
Take a look at what he's done
over close to 50 years.


2780
02:20:48.722 --> 02:20:51.222
There's certainly
a lot of variety.


2781
02:20:53.430 --> 02:20:57.722
There are
some things he's done
that haven't worked,


2782
02:20:57.722 --> 02:21:00.764
but there is absolutely
nobody like him


2783
02:21:00.764 --> 02:21:03.639
and no film career
trajectory


2784
02:21:03.639 --> 02:21:07.347
that is anything like his
in the history of film.


2785
02:21:07.347 --> 02:21:11.472
He speaks cinema
as if it's his native language.


2786
02:21:11.472 --> 02:21:14.263
He is so fluent in it
that he does things


2787
02:21:14.263 --> 02:21:16.305
that nobody else
would dare to do


2788
02:21:16.305 --> 02:21:18.722
and they are
instantly recognizable


2789
02:21:18.722 --> 02:21:21.847
as things
that are purely his.


2790
02:21:21.847 --> 02:21:25.805
Scorsese:
He has a dynamic sense
of real filmmaking.


2791
02:21:25.805 --> 02:21:27.513
I'm talking
about filmmaking of--


2792
02:21:27.513 --> 02:21:30.472
in the great
narrative tradition
of American cinema.


2793
02:21:30.472 --> 02:21:31.639
( distant explosion )

2794
02:21:31.639 --> 02:21:33.056
Coppola:
Steven was blessed


2795
02:21:33.056 --> 02:21:35.347
in that he could be
commercial


2796
02:21:35.347 --> 02:21:37.222
and he could do art.

2797
02:21:37.222 --> 02:21:39.513
That's why
I always compare him


2798
02:21:39.513 --> 02:21:41.097
to a kind
of George Gershwin,


2799
02:21:41.097 --> 02:21:43.680
because Gershwin
could write a Broadway show


2800
02:21:43.680 --> 02:21:46.097
or he could write
"Concerto in F."


2801
02:21:46.097 --> 02:21:48.847
He could both,
and very few people can do both.


2802
02:21:48.847 --> 02:21:50.722
And Steven can do both.

2803
02:21:50.722 --> 02:21:53.680
And that's a talent
you have to be born with.


2804
02:21:56.181 --> 02:21:57.972
DiCaprio:
You think of
that young kid in Arizona,


2805
02:21:57.972 --> 02:21:59.347
in the desert,
watching movies,


2806
02:21:59.347 --> 02:22:01.555
watching television
incessantly,


2807
02:22:01.555 --> 02:22:04.722
one day sneaking his way
into a studio,


2808
02:22:04.722 --> 02:22:07.014
and manifesting
his own destiny.


2809
02:22:07.014 --> 02:22:09.847
It's a pretty fantastic
Hollywood story.


2810
02:22:11.722 --> 02:22:14.597
J.J. Abrams:
He's found a way to take
his view of the world,


2811
02:22:14.597 --> 02:22:19.263
his wishful thinking,
his optimism,


2812
02:22:19.263 --> 02:22:23.347
and also his uncanny sense
of the thrill,


2813
02:22:23.347 --> 02:22:25.056
and sort of galvanize
the whole thing


2814
02:22:25.056 --> 02:22:27.847
into whatever the story is
he's telling.


2815
02:22:27.847 --> 02:22:30.222
It's authentically him.

2816
02:22:32.847 --> 02:22:34.722
Field:
Steven has a part of him


2817
02:22:34.722 --> 02:22:36.722
that wants to see
something good


2818
02:22:36.722 --> 02:22:38.430
in the darkest
of the dark


2819
02:22:38.430 --> 02:22:41.222
or that wants
to just have a playtime.


2820
02:22:45.764 --> 02:22:49.097
And there may be people
who say he's not edgy enough


2821
02:22:49.097 --> 02:22:53.222
or he's not bitter enough,
he's not quirky enough,


2822
02:22:53.222 --> 02:22:55.722
or he's not dark enough,

2823
02:22:55.722 --> 02:22:58.931
but when it's all over
and said and done,


2824
02:22:58.931 --> 02:23:02.931
what Steven has left
is enormous.


2825
02:23:04.597 --> 02:23:08.097
To have both humor
and suspense


2826
02:23:08.097 --> 02:23:10.639
and adventure and heart

2827
02:23:10.639 --> 02:23:14.430
through his grand eyes
of storytelling


2828
02:23:14.430 --> 02:23:17.847
is a hell of a good thing.

2829
02:23:17.847 --> 02:23:21.722
Day-Lewis:
Steven still has
an enormous appetite


2830
02:23:21.722 --> 02:23:23.931
for the work
that he does.


2831
02:23:23.931 --> 02:23:26.181
It's quite a rare thing.

2832
02:23:26.181 --> 02:23:29.597
You know, we all have,
probably, a shelf life.


2833
02:23:31.597 --> 02:23:34.847
Yes, we probably go
past that shelf life,


2834
02:23:34.847 --> 02:23:38.014
most of us,
without even knowing it.


2835
02:23:38.014 --> 02:23:42.472
But in his case, I think,
till the day he dies,
he'll be doing work


2836
02:23:42.472 --> 02:23:47.805
that he feels absolutely
viscerally compelled to do.


2837
02:23:55.639 --> 02:23:58.513
( music playing )